A Go-based payment workflow has been running in production for 8 months. The team needs to replace ActivityA with ActivityC. They deploy this patched code:

```go
v := workflow.GetVersion(ctx, "Step1", workflow.DefaultVersion, 1)
if v == workflow.DefaultVersion {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityA, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
} else {
    err = workflow.ExecuteActivity(ctx, ActivityC, data).Get(ctx, &result1)
}
```

Six months later (namespace retention is 30 days), all pre-patch workflows have long since completed. A new engineer, eager to clean up tech debt, changes `minSupported` from `workflow.DefaultVersion` to `1` and removes the ActivityA branch entirely. The same day, a workflow that was paused in a debugger for 2 hours (within normal operation bounds) resumes replay. What happens?

A .NET team is mid-way through the patching lifecycle for their order fulfillment workflow. They have deployed this code (Step 1 of 3 complete):

```csharp
public async Task RunAsync()
{
    if (Workflow.Patched("fulfillment-v2"))
    {
        this.result = await Workflow.ExecuteActivityAsync(
            (MyActivities a) => a.PostPatchActivity(),
            new() { StartToCloseTimeout = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5) });
    }
    else
    {
        this.result = await Workflow.ExecuteActivityAsync(
            (MyActivities a) => a.PrePatchActivity(),
            new() { StartToCloseTimeout = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5) });
    }
}
```

The namespace retention is set to 14 days. After 20 days, a junior engineer moves directly to Step 3 (removes both the `Patched` check and `DeprecatePatch`, deploying only PostPatchActivity). Two old Workers running the Step-1 code are still alive and processing tasks. What is the most precise description of the replay failure mode?
